  "body": "- fluentd version: 1.4.2\r\n- Environment information:\r\n  - Operating system: `16.04.6 LTS (Xenial Xerus)`\r\n  - Kernel version: `4.4.0-145-generic`\r\n- Your configuration\r\n```\r\n<source>\r\n  @type forward\r\n  bind 0.0.0.0\r\n  port 24224\r\n\r\n  <transport tls>\r\n    cert_path /fluentd/etc/fluentd.pem\r\n    private_key_path /fluentd/etc/fluentd.pem\r\n  </transport>\r\n</source>\r\n\r\n<match **>\r\n  @type null\r\n</match>\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt seems that fluentd start even if failed to parse certificate file in forward input with TLS.\r\n\r\nIf we use a certificate file that does not end with a newline (`\\n`), it will not match Fluentd's internal pattern[^1]. However Fluentd seems to start and listen on TLS connection. If you connect to Fluentd with TLS in this state, all handshakes will fail.\r\n\r\n[^1]: https://github.com/fluent/fluentd/blob/ea651827782d7ec92c3cd09cb6ada65e32bfab44/lib/fluent/plugin_helper/cert_option.rb#L171",
